Post.Content: In doing it, pays itself. Your Highness' part

Post.Content: To make thee full of growing. Noble Banquo,

Post.Content: In drops of sorrow. Sons, kinsmen, thanes,

Post.Content: But signs of nobleness, like stars, shall shine

Post.Content: On all deservers. From hence to Inverness,

Post.Content: MACBETH. Good repose the while.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: BANQUO. Thanks, sir, the like to you.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Exeunt Banquo. and Fleance.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. Go bid thy mistress, when my drink is ready,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: She strike upon the bell. Get thee to bed. Exit Servant.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Is this a dagger which I see before me,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: The handle toward my hand? Come, let me clutch thee.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: I have thee not, and yet I see thee still.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Art thou not, fatal vision, sensible
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: To feeling as to sight? Or art thou but
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: A dagger of the mind, a false creation,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Proceeding from the heat-oppressed brain?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: I see thee yet, in form as palpable
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: As this which now I draw.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Thou marshal'st me the way that I was going,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And such an instrument I was to use.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Mine eyes are made the fools o' the other senses,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Or else worth all the rest. I see thee still,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And on thy blade and dudgeon gouts of blood,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Which was not so before. There's no such thing:
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: It is the bloody business which informs
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Thus to mine eyes. Now o'er the one half-world
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Nature seems dead, and wicked dreams abuse
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The curtain'd sleep; witchcraft celebrates
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Pale Hecate's offerings; and wither'd Murther,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Alarum'd by his sentinel, the wolf,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Whose howl's his watch, thus with his stealthy pace,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: With Tarquin's ravishing strides, towards his design
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Moves like a ghost. Thou sure and firm-set earth,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Hear not my steps, which way they walk, for fear
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Thy very stones prate of my whereabout,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And take the present horror from the time,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Which now suits with it. Whiles I threat, he lives;
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Words to the heat of deeds too cold breath gives.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: A bell rings.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: I go, and it is done; the bell invites me.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Hear it not, Duncan, for it is a knell
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That summons thee to heaven, or to hell. Exit.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: SCENE II.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: The same.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Enter Lady Macbeth.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. That which hath made them drunk hath made me
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: bold;
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: What hath quench'd them hath given me fire. Hark! Peace!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: It was the owl that shriek'd, the fatal bellman,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Which gives the stern'st good night. He is about it:
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: The doors are open, and the surfeited grooms
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Do mock their charge with snores. I have drugg'd their
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: possets
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That death and nature do contend about them,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Whether they live or die.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. [Within.] Who's there' what, ho!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. Alack, I am afraid they have awaked
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: And 'tis not done. The attempt and not the deed
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Confounds us. Hark! I laid their daggers ready;
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: He could not miss 'em. Had he not resembled
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: My father as he slept, I had done't.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Enter Macbeth,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: My husband!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. I have done the deed. Didst thou not hear a noise?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. I heard the owl scream and the crickets cry.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Did not you speak?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. When?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. Now.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. As I descended?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. Ay.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. Hark!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Who lies i' the second chamber?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. Donalbain.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. This is a sorry sight. [Looks on his hands.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. A foolish thought, to say a sorry sight.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. There's one did laugh in 's sleep, and one cried,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: "Murther!"
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That they did wake each other. I stood and heard them,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: But they did say their prayers and address'd them
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Again to sleep.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. There are two lodged together.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. One cried, "God bless us!" and "Amen" the other,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: As they had seen me with these hangman's hands.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Listening their fear, I could not say "Amen,"
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: When they did say, "God bless us!"
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. Consider it not so deeply.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. But wherefore could not I pronounce "Amen"?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: I had most need of blessing, and "Amen"
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Stuck in my throat.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. These deeds must not be thought
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: After these ways; so, it will make us mad.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. I heard a voice cry, "Sleep no more!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Macbeth does murther sleep" -the innocent sleep,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Sleep that knits up the ravel'd sleave of care,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: The death of each day's life, sore labor's bath,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Balm of hurt minds, great nature's second course,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Chief nourisher in life's feast-
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. What do you mean?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. Still it cried, "Sleep no more!" to all the house;
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: "Glamis hath murther'd sleep, and therefore Cawdor
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Shall sleep no more. Macbeth shall sleep no more."
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. Who was it that thus cried? Why, worthy Thane,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: You do unbend your noble strength, to think
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: So brainsickly of things. Go, get some water
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And wash this filthy witness from your hand.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Why did you bring these daggers from the place?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: They must lie there. Go carry them, and smear
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: The sleepy grooms with blood.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. I'll go no more.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: I am afraid to think what I have done;
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Look on't again I dare not.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. Infirm of purpose!
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Give me the daggers. The sleeping and the dead
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Are but as pictures; 'tis the eye of childhood
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: That fears a painted devil. If he do bleed,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: I'll gild the faces of the grooms withal,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: For it must seem their guilt. Exit. Knocking within.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Whence is that knocking?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: How is't with me, when every noise appals me?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: What hands are here? Ha, they pluck out mine eyes!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Will all great Neptune's ocean wash this blood
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Clean from my hand? No, this my hand will rather
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: The multitudinous seas incarnadine,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Making the green one red.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Re-enter Lady Macbeth.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. My hands are of your color, but I shame
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: To wear a heart so white. [Knocking within.] I hear knocking
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: At the south entry. Retire we to our chamber.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: A little water clears us of this deed.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: How easy is it then! Your constancy
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Hath left you unattended. [Knocking within.] Hark, more
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: knocking.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Get on your nightgown, lest occasion call us
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And show us to be watchers. Be not lost
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: So poorly in your thoughts.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. To know my deed, 'twere best not know myself.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Knocking within.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Wake Duncan with thy knocking! I would thou couldst!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Exeunt.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SCENE III.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: The same.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Enter a Porter. Knocking within.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: PORTER. Here's a knocking indeed! If a man were porter of Hell
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Gate, he should have old turning the key. [Knocking within.]
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Knock, knock, knock! Who's there, i' the name of Belzebub?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Here's
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: a farmer that hanged himself on th' expectation of plenty.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Come
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: in time! Have napkins enow about you; here you'll sweat fort.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: [Knocking within.] Knock, knock! Who's there, in th' other
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: devil's name? Faith, here's an equivocator that could swear
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: in
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: both the scales against either scale, who committed treason
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: enough for God's sake, yet could not equivocate to heaven. O,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: come in, equivocator. [Knocking within.] Knock, knock, knock!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Who's there? Faith, here's an English tailor come hither, for
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: stealing out of a French hose. Come in, tailor; here you may
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: roast your goose. [Knocking within.] Knock, knock! Never at
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: quiet! What are you? But this place is too cold for hell.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: I'll
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: devil-porter it no further. I had thought to have let in some
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: of
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: all professions, that go the primrose way to the everlasting
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: bonfire. [Knocking within.] Anon, anon! I pray you, remember
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: the
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: porter.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Opens the gate.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Enter Macduff and Lennox.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Was it so late, friend, ere you went to bed,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: That you do lie so late?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: PORTER. Faith, sir, we were carousing till the second cock; and
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: drink, sir, is a great provoker of three things.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACDUFF. What three things does drink especially provoke?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: PORTER. Marry, sir, nose-painting, sleep, and urine. Lechery,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: sir,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: it provokes and unprovokes: it provokes the desire, but it
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: takes
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: away the performance. Therefore much drink may be said to be
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: an
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: equivocator with lechery: it makes him, and it mars him; it
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: sets
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: him on, and it takes him off; it persuades him and
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: disheartens
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: him; makes him stand to and not stand to; in conclusion,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: equivocates him in a sleep, and giving him the lie, leaves
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: him.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACDUFF. I believe drink gave thee the lie last night.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: PORTER. That it did, sir, i' the very throat on me; but
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: requited
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: him for his lie, and, I think, being too strong for him,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: though
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: he took up my legs sometime, yet I made shift to cast him.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Is thy master stirring?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Enter Macbeth.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Our knocking has awaked him; here he comes.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: LENNOX. Good morrow, noble sir.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. morrow, both.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Is the King stirring, worthy Thane?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Not yet.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACDUFF. He did command me to call timely on him;
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: I have almost slipp'd the hour.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. I'll bring you to him.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACDUFF. I know this is a joyful trouble to you,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: But yet 'tis one.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. The labor we delight in physics pain.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: This is the door.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACDUFF I'll make so bold to call,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: For 'tis my limited service. Exit.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: LENNOX. Goes the King hence today?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. He does; he did appoint so.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: LENNOX. The night has been unruly. Where we lay,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Our chimneys were blown down, and, as they say,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Lamentings heard i' the air, strange screams of death,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: And prophesying with accents terrible
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Of dire combustion and confused events
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: New hatch'd to the woeful time. The obscure bird
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Clamor'd the livelong night. Some say the earth
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Was feverous and did shake.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. 'Twas a rough fight.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: LENNOX. My young remembrance cannot parallel
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: A fellow to it.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Re-enter Macduff.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACDUFF. O horror, horror, horror! Tongue nor heart
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Cannot conceive nor name thee.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. LENNOX. What's the matter?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Confusion now hath made his masterpiece.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Most sacrilegious murther hath broke ope
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: The Lord's anointed temple and stole thence
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The life o' the building.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. What is't you say? the life?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: LENNOX. Mean you his Majesty?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Approach the chamber, and destroy your sight
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: With a new Gorgon. Do not bid me speak;
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: See, and then speak yourselves.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Exeunt Macbeth and Lennox.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Awake, awake!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Ring the alarum bell. Murther and treason!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Banquo and Donalbain! Malcolm, awake!
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Shake off this downy sleep, death's counterfeit,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And look on death itself! Up, up, and see
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The great doom's image! Malcolm! Banquo!
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: As from your graves rise up, and walk like sprites
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: To countenance this horror! Ring the bell. Bell rings.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Enter Lady Macbeth.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. What's the business,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That such a hideous trumpet calls to parley
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The sleepers of the house? Speak, speak!
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACDUFF. O gentle lady,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: 'Tis not for you to hear what I can speak:
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The repetition in a woman's ear
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Would murther as it fell.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Enter Banquo.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: O Banquo, Banquo!
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Our royal master's murther'd.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. Woe, alas!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: What, in our house?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: BANQUO. Too cruel anywhere.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Dear Duff, I prithee, contradict thyself,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: And say it is not so.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Re-enter Macbeth and Lennox, with Ross.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. Had I but died an hour before this chance,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: I had lived a blessed time, for from this instant
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: There's nothing serious in mortality.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: All is but toys; renown and grace is dead,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The wine of life is drawn, and the mere lees
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Is left this vault to brag of.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Enter Malcolm and Donalbain.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: DONALBAIN. What is amiss?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. You are, and do not know't.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: The spring, the head, the fountain of your blood
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Is stopped, the very source of it is stopp'd.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Your royal father's murther'd.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MALCOLM. O, by whom?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: LENNOX. Those of his chamber, as it seem'd, had done't.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Their hands and faces were all badged with blood;
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: So were their daggers, which unwiped we found
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Upon their pillows.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: They stared, and were distracted; no man's life
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Was to be trusted with them.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. O, yet I do repent me of my fury,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: That I did kill them.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Wherefore did you so?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Who can be wise, amazed, temperate and furious,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Loyal and neutral, in a moment? No man.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: The expedition of my violent love
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Outrun the pauser reason. Here lay Duncan,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: His silver skin laced with his golden blood,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And his gash'd stabs look'd like a breach in nature
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: For ruin's wasteful entrance; there, the murtherers,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Steep'd in the colors of their trade, their daggers
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Unmannerly breech'd with gore. Who could refrain,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: That had a heart to love, and in that heart
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Courage to make 's love known?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: LADY MACBETH. Help me hence, ho!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Look to the lady.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MALCOLM. [Aside to Donalbain.] Why do we hold our tongues,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That most may claim this argument for ours?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: DONALBAIN. [Aside to Malcolm.] What should be spoken here,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: where
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: our fate,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Hid in an auger hole, may rush and seize us?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Let's away,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Our tears are not yet brew'd.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MALCOLM. [Aside to Donalbain.] Nor our strong sorrow
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Upon the foot of motion.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: BANQUO. Look to the lady.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Lady Macbeth is carried out.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And when we have our naked frailties hid,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That suffer in exposure, let us meet
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: And question this most bloody piece of work
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: To know it further. Fears and scruples shake us.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: In the great hand of God I stand, and thence
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Against the undivulged pretense I fight
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Of treasonous malice.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACDUFF. And so do I.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: ALL. So all.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. Let's briefly put on manly readiness
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And meet i' the hall together.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: ALL. Well contented.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Exeunt all but Malcolm and Donalbain.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MALCOLM. What will you do? Let's not consort with them.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: To show an unfelt sorrow is an office
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Which the false man does easy. I'll to England.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: DONALBAIN. To Ireland, I; our separated fortune
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Shall keep us both the safer. Where we are
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: There's daggers in men's smiles; the near in blood,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: The nearer bloody.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MALCOLM. This murtherous shaft that's shot
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Hath not yet lighted, and our safest way
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Is to avoid the aim. Therefore to horse;
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: And let us not be dainty of leave-taking,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: But shift away. There's warrant in that theft
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Which steals itself when there's no mercy left.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Exeunt.

Post.Content: Now minutely revolts upbraid his faith-breach;
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Those he commands move only in command,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Nothing in love. Now does he feel his title
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Hang loose about him, like a giant's robe
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Upon a dwarfish thief.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MENTEITH. Who then shall blame
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: His pester'd senses to recoil and start,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: When all that is within him does condemn
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Itself for being there?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: CAITHNESS. Well, march we on
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: To give obedience where 'tis truly owed.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Meet we the medicine of the sickly weal,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And with him pour we, in our country's purge,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Each drop of us.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: LENNOX. Or so much as it needs
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: To dew the sovereign flower and drown the weeds.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Make we our march towards Birnam. Exeunt marching.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SCENE III.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Dunsinane. A room in the castle.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Enter Macbeth, Doctor, and Attendants.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. Bring me no more reports; let them fly all!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Till Birnam Wood remove to Dunsinane
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: I cannot taint with fear. What's the boy Malcolm?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Was he not born of woman? The spirits that know
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: All mortal consequences have pronounced me thus:
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: "Fear not, Macbeth; no man that's born of woman
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Shall e'er have power upon thee." Then fly, false Thanes,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And mingle with the English epicures!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The mind I sway by and the heart I bear
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Shall never sag with doubt nor shake with fear.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Enter a Servant.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The devil damn thee black, thou cream-faced loon!
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Where got'st thou that goose look?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: SERVANT. There is ten thousand-
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Geese, villain?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SERVANT. Soldiers, sir.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. Go prick thy face and over-red thy fear,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Thou lily-liver'd boy. What soldiers, patch?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Death of thy soul! Those linen cheeks of thine
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Are counselors to fear. What soldiers, whey-face?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: SERVANT. The English force, so please you.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. Take thy face hence. Exit Servant.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Seyton-I am sick at heart,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: When I behold- Seyton, I say!- This push
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Will cheer me ever or disseat me now.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: I have lived long enough. My way of life
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Is fall'n into the sear, the yellow leaf,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And that which should accompany old age,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: As honor, love, obedience, troops of friends,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: I must not look to have; but in their stead,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Curses, not loud but deep, mouth-honor, breath,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Which the poor heart would fain deny and dare not.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Seyton!
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Enter Seyton.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: SEYTON. What's your gracious pleasure?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. What news more?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SEYTON. All is confirm'd, my lord, which was reported.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. I'll fight, 'til from my bones my flesh be hack'd.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Give me my armor.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SEYTON. 'Tis not needed yet.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. I'll put it on.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Send out more horses, skirr the country round,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Hang those that talk of fear. Give me mine armor.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: How does your patient, doctor?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: DOCTOR. Not so sick, my lord,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: As she is troubled with thick-coming fancies,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That keep her from her rest.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Cure her of that.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Canst thou not minister to a mind diseased,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Pluck from the memory a rooted sorrow,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Raze out the written troubles of the brain,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And with some sweet oblivious antidote
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Cleanse the stuff'd bosom of that perilous stuff
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Which weighs upon the heart?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: DOCTOR. Therein the patient
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Must minister to himself.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Throw physic to the dogs, I'll none of it.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Come, put mine armor on; give me my staff.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Seyton, send out. Doctor, the Thanes fly from me.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Come, sir, dispatch. If thou couldst, doctor, cast
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: The water of my land, find her disease
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And purge it to a sound and pristine health,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: I would applaud thee to the very echo,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: That should applaud again. Pull't off, I say.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: What rhubarb, cyme, or what purgative drug
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Would scour these English hence? Hearst thou of them?
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: DOCTOR. Ay, my good lord, your royal preparation
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Makes us hear something.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Bring it after me.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: I will not be afraid of death and bane
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Till Birnam Forest come to Dunsinane.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: DOCTOR. [Aside.] Were I from Dunsinane away and clear,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Profit again should hardly draw me here. Exeunt.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: SCENE IV.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Country near Birnam Wood. Drum and colors.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Enter Malcolm, old Seward and his Son, Macduff, Menteith,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Caithness,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Angus, Lennox, Ross, and Soldiers, marching.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MALCOLM. Cousins, I hope the days are near at hand
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That chambers will be safe.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MENTEITH. We doubt it nothing.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SIWARD. What wood is this before us?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MENTEITH. The Wood of Birnam.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MALCOLM. Let every soldier hew him down a bough,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And bear't before him; thereby shall we shadow
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: The numbers of our host, and make discovery
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Err in report of us.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SOLDIERS. It shall be done.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: SIWARD. We learn no other but the confident tyrant
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Keeps still in Dunsinane and will endure
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Our setting down before't.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MALCOLM. 'Tis his main hope;
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: For where there is advantage to be given,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Both more and less have given him the revolt,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And none serve with him but constrained things
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Whose hearts are absent too.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Let our just censures
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Attend the true event, and put we on
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Industrious soldiership.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SIWARD. The time approaches
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That will with due decision make us know
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: What we shall say we have and what we owe.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Thoughts speculative their unsure hopes relate,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: But certain issue strokes must arbitrate.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Towards which advance the war.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Exeunt Marching.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: SCENE V.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Dunsinane. Within the castle.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Enter Macbeth, Seyton, and Soldiers, with drum and colors.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. Hang out our banners on the outward walls;
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The cry is still, "They come!" Our castle's strength
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Will laugh a siege to scorn. Here let them lie
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Till famine and the ague eat them up.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Were they not forced with those that should be ours,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: We might have met them dareful, beard to beard,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And beat them backward home.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: A cry of women within.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: What is that noise?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: SEYTON. It is the cry of women, my good lord. Exit.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. I have almost forgot the taste of fears:
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: The time has been, my senses would have cool'd
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: To hear a night-shriek, and my fell of hair
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Would at a dismal treatise rouse and stir
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: As life were in't. I have supp'd full with horrors;
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Direness, familiar to my slaughterous thoughts,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Cannot once start me.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Re-enter Seyton.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Wherefore was that cry?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: SEYTON. The Queen, my lord, is dead.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. She should have died hereafter;
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: There would have been a time for such a word.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Tomorrow, and tomorrow, and tomorrow
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Creeps in this petty pace from day to day
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: To the last syllable of recorded time;
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: And all our yesterdays have lighted fools
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: The way to dusty death. Out, out, brief candle!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Life's but a walking shadow, a poor player
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: That struts and frets his hour upon the stage
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And then is heard no more. It is a tale
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Told by an idiot, full of sound and fury,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Signifying nothing.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Enter a Messenger.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Thou comest to use thy tongue; thy story quickly.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MESSENGER. Gracious my lord,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: I should report that which I say I saw,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: But know not how to do it.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Well, say, sir.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MESSENGER. As I did stand my watch upon the hill,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: I look'd toward Birnam, and anon, methought,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The Wood began to move.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. Liar and slave!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MESSENGER. Let me endure your wrath, if't be not so.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Within this three mile may you see it coming;
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: I say, a moving grove.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACBETH. If thou speak'st false,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Upon the next tree shalt thou hang alive,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Till famine cling thee; if thy speech be sooth,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: I care not if thou dost for me as much.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: I pull in resolution and begin
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: To doubt the equivocation of the fiend
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That lies like truth. "Fear not, till Birnam Wood
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Do come to Dunsinane," and now a wood
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Comes toward Dunsinane. Arm, arm, and out!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: If this which he avouches does appear,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: There is nor flying hence nor tarrying here.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: I 'gin to be aweary of the sun
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And wish the estate o' the world were now undone.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Ring the alarum bell! Blow, wind! Come, wrack!
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: At least we'll die with harness on our back. Exeunt.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: SCENE VI.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Dunsinane. Before the castle.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Enter Malcolm, old Siward, Macduff, and their Army, with boughs.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Drum and colors.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MALCOLM. Now near enough; your leavy screens throw down,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And show like those you are. You, worthy uncle,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Shall with my cousin, your right noble son,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Lead our first battle. Worthy Macduff and we
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Shall take upon 's what else remains to do,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: According to our order.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: SIWARD. Fare you well.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Do we but find the tyrant's power tonight,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Let us be beaten if we cannot fight.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Make all our trumpets speak, give them all breath,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Those clamorous harbingers of blood and death.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Exeunt.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: SCENE VII.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Dunsinane. Before the castle. Alarums.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Enter Macbeth.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. They have tied me to a stake; I cannot fly,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: But bear-like I must fight the course. What's he
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That was not born of woman? Such a one
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Am I to fear, or none.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Enter young Siward.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: YOUNG SIWARD. What is thy name?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Thou'lt be afraid to hear it.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: YOUNG SIWARD. No, though thou call'st thyself a hotter name
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Than any is in hell.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. My name's Macbeth.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: YOUNG SIWARD. The devil himself could not pronounce a title
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: More hateful to mine ear.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. No, nor more fearful.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: YOUNG SIWARD O Thou liest, abhorred tyrant; with my sword
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: I'll prove the lie thou speak'st.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: They fight, and young Seward is slain.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. Thou wast born of woman.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: But swords I smile at, weapons laugh to scorn,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Brandish'd by man that's of a woman born. Exit.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Alarums. Enter Macduff.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACDUFF. That way the noise is. Tyrant, show thy face!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: If thou best slain and with no stroke of mine,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: My wife and children's ghosts will haunt me still.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: I cannot strike at wretched kerns, whose arms
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Are hired to bear their staves. Either thou, Macbeth,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Or else my sword, with an unbatter'd edge,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: I sheathe again undeeded. There thou shouldst be;
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: By this great clatter, one of greatest note
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Seems bruited. Let me find him, Fortune!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And more I beg not. Exit. Alarums.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Enter Malcolm and old Siward.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SIWARD. This way, my lord; the castle's gently render'd.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: The tyrant's people on both sides do fight,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The noble Thanes do bravely in the war,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: The day almost itself professes yours,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And little is to do.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MALCOLM. We have met with foes
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: That strike beside us.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: SIWARD. Enter, sir, the castle.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Exeunt. Alarum.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SCENE VIII.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Another part of the field.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Enter Macbeth.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. Why should I play the Roman fool and die
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: On mine own sword? Whiles I see lives, the gashes
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Do better upon them.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Enter Macduff.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Turn, hell hound, turn!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Of all men else I have avoided thee.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: But get thee back, my soul is too much charged
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: With blood of thine already.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACDUFF. I have no words.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: My voice is in my sword, thou bloodier villain
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Than terms can give thee out! They fight.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. Thou losest labor.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: As easy mayst thou the intrenchant air
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: With thy keen sword impress as make me bleed.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Let fall thy blade on vulnerable crests;
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: I bear a charmed life, which must not yield
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: To one of woman born.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Despair thy charm,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And let the angel whom thou still hast served
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Tell thee, Macduff was from his mother's womb
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Untimely ripp'd.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACBETH. Accursed be that tongue that tells me so,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: For it hath cow'd my better part of man!
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: And be these juggling fiends no more believed
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: That patter with us in a double sense,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That keep the word of promise to our ear
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: And break it to our hope. I'll not fight with thee.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Then yield thee, coward,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And live to be the show and gaze o' the time.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: We'll have thee, as our rarer monsters are,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Painted upon a pole, and underwrit,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: "Here may you see the tyrant."
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MACBETH. I will not yield,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: To kiss the ground before young Malcolm's feet,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And to be baited with the rabble's curse.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Though Birnam Wood be come to Dunsinane,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And thou opposed, being of no woman born,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Yet I will try the last. Before my body
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: I throw my warlike shield! Lay on, Macduff,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And damn'd be him that first cries, "Hold, enough!"
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Exeunt fighting. Alarums.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: SCENE IX.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Retreat. Flourish. Enter, with drum and colors, Malcolm, old
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Siward, Ross,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: the other Thanes, and Soldiers.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MALCOLM. I would the friends we miss were safe arrived.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: SIWARD. Some must go off, and yet, by these I see,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: So great a day as this is cheaply bought.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: MALCOLM. Macduff is missing, and your noble son.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: ROSS. Your son, my lord, has paid a soldier's debt.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: He only lived but till he was a man,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: The which no sooner had his prowess confirm'd
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: In the unshrinking station where he fought,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: But like a man he died.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SIWARD. Then he is dead?
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: ROSS. Ay, and brought off the field. Your cause of sorrow
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Must not be measured by his worth, for then
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: It hath no end.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: SIWARD. Had he his hurts before?
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: ROSS. Ay, on the front.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SIWARD. Why then, God's soldier be he!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Had I as many sons as I have hairs,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: I would not wish them to a fairer death.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: And so his knell is knoll'd.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MALCOLM. He's worth more sorrow,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: And that I'll spend for him.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: SIWARD. He's worth no more:
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: They say he parted well and paid his score,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: And so God be with him! Here comes newer comfort.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Re-enter Macduff, with Macbeth's head.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: MACDUFF. Hail, King, for so thou art. Behold where stands
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: The usurper's cursed head. The time is free.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: I see thee compass'd with thy kingdom's pearl
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: That speak my salutation in their minds,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Whose voices I desire aloud with mine-
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Hail, King of Scotland!
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: ALL. Hail, King of Scotland! Flourish.
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: MALCOLM. We shall not spend a large expense of time
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Before we reckon with your several loves
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: And make us even with you. My Thanes and kinsmen,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Henceforth be Earls, the first that ever Scotland
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: In such an honor named. What's more to do,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Which would be planted newly with the time,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: As calling home our exiled friends abroad
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: That fled the snares of watchful tyranny,
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Producing forth the cruel ministers
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Of this dead butcher and his fiend-like queen,
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Who, as 'tis thought, by self and violent hands
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: Took off her life; this, and what needful else
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: That calls upon us, by the grace of Grace
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: We will perform in measure, time, and place.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: So thanks to all at once and to each one,
Post.Author: user3

Post.Content: Whom we invite to see us crown'd at Scone.
Post.Author: user4

Post.Content: Flourish. Exeunt.
Post.Author: user1

Post.Content: -THE END-
